Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

By Donnelly Miller¶

Prosper loan investigation goal¶

Borrowing money seems to be a way of life for many people. There are many reasons borrowers will request a loan. When it comes to borrowing money, many factors can potentially affect the outcome of the loan. The main goal is to pay off the debt by incurring as extra debt as possible. Unfortunately, not all loans are paid on time, and some are charged off or defaulted on. The goal of this investigation is to examine the relationships between variables that may suggest increased ore decreases risks in a borrower's ability to pay back a loan. A large part of repaying back a loan involves paying interest on top of the original loan amount. Another goal of this investigation is to determine what factors might contribute to paying lower interest and how in turn this might affect the status of the loan. How might factors that contribute to both interest rate and loan status be related? This investigation will address two questions.

Primary question to be investigated: What factors might contribute to the status of a loan?¶

Secondary question to be investigated: What factors might contribute to a higher interest rate?¶

The process begins by doing some univariate data exploration. Following the univariate exploration, the following sets of slides focus on the bivariate aspect and finally concluding with the multivariate exploration where we get some insights on to the possible risk factors for higher interests' rates and negative loan statuses.

Variables that might be worth investigating to address the questions:¶

  • Credit score
  • Number of open credit lines
  • Income
  • Employment status
  • Term length of the loan
  • Interest rate
  • Debt to income ratio
  • Prosper score
  • Original loan amount
  • Required montly payment

Updated Dataset Structure¶

There is information on 113,937 loans on this dataset. Several variables are associated with this dataset some of which include credit scores, employment status, income, number of open credit lines, occupation, and current delinquencies. There are several both numeric and categorical variables. Some of the categorical variables have been ordered.

The following bar graph displays in order, from greatest to least, the reasons why borrowers requests loans. Debt consolidation ranks the top reason for requesting loans.

Prosper ratings are used to allow potential investors to consider the loan application and the possible estimated average annual loss rate. A Prosper rating of AA presents the lowest risk, with HR posing as the greatest risk. The sequential order of risk level from greatest to least (NC, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA). Note that for Credit Grade there is an NC for loans originating prior to 2009.

In looking at the following facet grid of histograms, the darker regions indicate a larger concentration of borrowers with higher Prosper scores and lower interests rates were more likely to have current and or completed loans. We can see a shift in the patter in loans that are past due. For loans that are defaulted or charged off we see that there is a concentration of borrower's that have lower Prosper scores in combination with higher interests' rates. This demonstrates that higher interests' rates coupled with lower Prosper scores may present an increased risk for Prosper.

The following heatmap shows that higher income levels along with lower median interest rates appear to be more favorable for positive loan outcomes. We can see there is a trend towards negative loan outcomes as the median interests' rate goes up along with lower income. The combination of lower income coupled with higher interests' rates indicate an increased risk of borrowers not being able to repay the lender.

Being that Prosper scores and interests' rates have a solid moderate negative correlation, we see a similar pattern in the following heatmap in which higher incomes along with higher Prosper scores are favorable for positive loan outcomes. We see an unfavorable trend as both Prosper scores and income levels drop. Borrowers with higher credit ratings, lower interests' rates, and higher incomes may in fact pose a reduced risk for lenders.

cat_counts2 = df_loan.groupby(['LoanStatus', 'IncomeRange']).median()['ProsperScore'] * 1
cat_counts2 = cat_counts2.reset_index(name = 'MedianProsperScore')
cat_counts2 = cat_counts2.pivot(index = 'IncomeRange',columns = 'LoanStatus', values = 'MedianProsperScore')

plt.figure(figsize = (6, 6))
sn.heatmap(cat_counts2, annot = True, cmap = 'RdYlBu', fmt = '.1f', cbar_kws = {'label': 'Median Prosper Score'})
plt.ylabel('Borrower Income Range')
plt.xlabel('Borrower Loan Status')
plt.title('Median Borrower Prosper Score by Income Range and Loan Status');
